DataElement.preferredName: Laboratory Procedure Normal Reference Range Institution Serum Alpha-Fetoprotein Outcome ng/mL Value
DataElement.preferredDefinition: The value associated with a normal laboratory procedure result (reported values within the typical or expected range) for the level of alpha-fetoprotein in the blood serum (the clear liquid part of the blood that remains after blood cells and clotting proteins have been removed) at an institution (an established organization founded and united for a specific purpose, e.g. for health-related research) measured in ng/mL.

Property.preferredName: Normal Reference Range Institution Serum Alpha-Fetoprotein Outcome
Property.preferredDefinition: Reported values within the typical or expected range.:An established society, corporation, foundation or other organization founded and united for a specific purpose, e.g. for health-related research as, a literary institution; also, a building or the buildings occupied or used by such organization.:The clear liquid part of the blood that remains after blood cells and clotting proteins have been removed.:Alpha-fetoprotein. A protein normally produced by a developing fetus. AFP levels are usually undetectable in the blood of healthy nonpregnant adults. An elevated level of AFP suggests the presence of either a primary liver cancer or germ cell tumor.:The result of an action.

Concepts.definition: Reported values within the typical or expected range.

An established society, corporation, foundation or other organization founded and united for a specific purpose, e.g. for health-related research; also used to refer to a building or buildings occupied or used by such organization.
The clear portion of the blood that remains after the removal of the blood cells and the clotting proteins.
Alpha-fetoprotein (609 aa, ~69 kDa) is encoded by the human AFP gene. This protein plays a role in the binding to copper, nickel, bilirubin and fatty acids in the fetal circulation.
